09:08.843 --> 09:13.548
I parked my truck on the street next to the handball 
court so I would have a good parking place. At 4

09:14.729 --> 09:17.652
a.m., the street cleaner woke me up. And it was much 
like Christmas Day when I was a child. I could not go

09:21.382 --> 09:26.512
back to sleep, even though I had only been asleep 
for three hours. At six, I went to the dorm,

09:27.513 --> 09:31.380
showered and dressed in Aggie senior uniform. At 
eight, I filled out papers and was sworn in by

09:31.420 --> 09:36.349
Colonel Blake. At 10 o'clock graduation began and 
lasted until noon, General Rutter talked too

09:36.700 --> 09:42.246
long. And one of the things, I've given lots and 
lots of speeches. My speeches are all short. And I

09:50.095 --> 09:57.844
gave the commissioning speech here in May last 
year, and it was nine minutes long. I said, look,

09:57.944 --> 10:00.607
just tell me how long it is. And it was nine minutes. 
And I got the Board of Regents. I got six letters

10:06.599 --> 10:08.462
from the Board of Regents. They said they'd never 
had a nine-minute speech before. And I said, you

10:11.968 --> 10:14.332
know, you don't have to have a good speech if it's 
short. I saw Jeannie and Marilyn, that's my

10:15.253 --> 10:23.286
sister, for just a few minutes because I had to 
change into my army greens for commissioning.

10:24.067 --> 10:26.471
Commissioning was a very impressive ceremony. 
General James K. Woolnock, Woolnock, Kornark

10:30.025 --> 10:39.594
Commander, four-star, gave me my commission, 
which I had to give back because it was a reserve and

10:30.025 --> 10:39.594
not a regular commission. They'd made a mistake 
because I was commissioned as a regular officer.

10:43.397 --> 10:45.359
Jeannie and Marilyn pinned my bars on. My mama and 
daddy had the flu and were very sick and didn't

10:45.479 --> 10:49.783
come. I was saluted and gave away a dollar bill, 
which, you know, is a tradition. And...

10:59.455 --> 11:04.643
told everybody goodbye and drove to Fort Benning, 
Georgia. So I was commissioned, graduated, and

11:05.664 --> 11:11.673
left for Fort Benning on January the 20th. How well 
prepared did you believe A&M had made you? How well

11:18.443 --> 11:22.850
prepared were you for what you thought was your 
future? Well, yeah, at that time.

11:32.547 --> 11:44.537
What I think A&M did was, and it may have been ROTC 
summer camp, tied in, but I was confident, but

11:32.547 --> 11:44.537
never overconfident.

11:45.238 --> 11:52.624
I finished all my Army schools, either the honor 
graduate or in the top 1% or 2%. None of them were

11:53.045 --> 11:58.389
hard. Went to airborne school, and I remember I 
went to airborne school after ranger school and

12:02.230 --> 12:20.880
the airborne school sergeants were black hats and 
they thought they were mean and tough and this one

12:02.230 --> 12:20.880
sergeant is yelling at me and I'm a second 
lieutenant and I've been through OBC and ranger

12:02.230 --> 12:20.880
school and I was an honor graduate from ranger 
school. And an airborne school physically is a

12:21.620 --> 12:26.989
piece of cake compared to ranger school. And I was 
in superb condition, always was. And this

12:30.375 --> 12:32.419
sergeant's yelling at me about something. And he 
finally asked me a question or something or

12:33.421 --> 12:38.229
allowed me to speak. And I said, Sarge, I hate to 
tell you this, but you're a rookie compared to an

12:39.150 --> 12:44.640
Aggie pisshead. And he had no clue what I was 
talking about, but he knew that it was not

12:45.447 --> 12:50.414
favorable. And he got so mad, and he just stormed 
off and everything. But, you know, no, I think the

12:54.879 --> 13:04.452
Aggie program and the experience...

13:06.642 --> 13:08.665
You know, just plus my raising. I mean, I was raised 
in the woods. I was raised by a grand... You know, my

13:11.409 --> 13:16.315
grandfather just spent a tremendous amount of 
time with me. And I was always very confident of my

13:16.616 --> 13:24.407
ability to do physical hand-eye coordination. I 
mean, anything like that. I mean, you know, if I

13:25.648 --> 13:30.595
went into a GRE exam, I wasn't ever confident. But 
if I was having to do something where... your wits

13:35.397 --> 13:44.350
depended upon it or your calmness or your 
decision-making or your ability to accomplish or

13:35.397 --> 13:44.350
overcome an obstacle.

13:46.993 --> 13:50.438
I was just confident without being 
overconfident. Did A&M help to build that

13:50.819 --> 13:52.702
confidence? Well, I think it was the whole 
program. I was very gifted to have a wonderful

13:55.946 --> 14:02.215
family that kind of... you know, kind of continued 
along with A&M. And then I think A&M just because

14:07.222 --> 14:10.382
of... of all the experiences and the traditions 
that you put in in such an important period of your

14:10.835 --> 14:17.763
life. And it was very disciplined. I mean, A&M was a 
very disciplined place, and I liked that. And so I

14:24.472 --> 14:27.275
think it just fit very well for me. It was one of 
those things, like I tell folks, the Army's not for

14:27.595 --> 14:32.682
everybody, but for some people it's perfect. And 
A&M's not for everybody, but for some people it's

14:32.722 --> 14:36.426
just perfect. And it was... I was a... I was a rebel 
without being a troublemaker. I wasn't a

14:41.761 --> 14:43.343
follower. I would not just do things because I 
thought through things. And A&M, the whole

14:52.034 --> 14:58.341
experience lets you figure all that out for 
yourself. This Aggie spirit that all of us refer

14:58.361 --> 15:05.490
to, what is it, what makes it, and why is it 
important? I saw that... in your paper and I've

15:07.720 --> 15:22.938
been thinking about it because I've read where 
some very gifted people have written some really

15:07.720 --> 15:22.938
neat things about what the Aggie spirit means to 
them. What it means to me is things like, is the

15:25.621 --> 15:34.251
personal, aspects of things happening like 
